{
  "doc_id": "23429",
  "text": "The diabetic drug tolbutamide was chosen as a substrate because of its low extraction ratio and because it is used as a reference compound in many kinetic studies [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Furthermore, it enables the comparison with the in vitro method using liver slices [CITATION_4] . Hepatocytes cultured between two layers of collagen maintain many in vivo characteristics. This resemblance to the in vivo situation is important especially when results are to be extrapolated. Nevertheless, for accurate modeling it was important to monitor some culture characteristics over the same period tolbutamide metabolism was measured. These data were used to correct the calculated intrinsic clearance and involved cell viability, protein content, and enzyme activity. Cell viability and protein content only slightly decreased. For enzyme activity, only the major enzyme responsible for the metabolism of tolbutamide into hydroxytolbutamide, CYP2C11 [CITATION_5] , was considered. The enzyme activity decreased much faster than viability, reducing metabolizing capacity and showing the necessity of these corrections. Cells cultured after a liver perfusion comprise more than 90% of hepatocytes; therefore, these values were used without further adjustment. Moreover, these values were in agreement with literature values [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] .",
